  <h2 id="common-mistakes">Common mistakes to avoid</h2>
  <h3>Changing dose, yield, and grind all at once</h3>
  <p>This is the fastest way to lose signal. Keep dose and yield fixed first, then move grind. Once flavor stabilizes, you can fine-tune other variables.</p>

  <h3>Ignoring bean age and environment shifts</h3>
  <p>Beans degas and humidity moves extraction behavior. If your setting drifted after a few days, that is normal. Make a small correction and retest instead of resetting your entire recipe.</p>

  <h3>Skipping grinder maintenance</h3>
  <p>Old fines and coffee oils build up quickly in espresso ranges. That buildup can make your shot times inconsistent even if your puck prep is solid. Clean lightly every few days and deep-clean monthly.</p>

  <h3>Assuming one setting works for all roasts</h3>
  <p>Light roasts usually need finer settings than darker roasts for similar extraction. Keep separate notes by coffee so you can recover good ranges immediately.</p>

  <h2>Example dial-in log you can copy</h2>
  <p>A simple dial-in log beats memory every time. Keep one note per bag with date, dose, yield, shot time, and taste. Here is a practical structure: Day 1 starts at 18g in, 36g out, 22 seconds, sour finish, then one click finer. Day 2 lands at 26 seconds, balanced sweetness, and mild acidity. Day 4 drifts to 23 seconds because the coffee degassed, so you move one click finer again. This pattern is normal and helps you avoid full resets.</p>
  <p>When you switch to a new coffee, copy your last stable recipe and adjust from there. Lighter coffees often need finer settings and slightly longer contact time to build sweetness. Darker coffees often run better a touch coarser to avoid bitter, hollow finish. Treat the log as a map, not a strict formula. The value is speed and consistency, not perfect numbers.</p>
  <p>If you are sharing one grinder across multiple people, agree on named presets. For example: "Morning blend espresso" and "Weekend light roast." Put those labels near the grinder so settings do not drift without tracking. That one habit reduces accidental changes and saves both beans and time.</p>

  <h2>Roast-level adjustment cheat sheet</h2>
  <p>Roast level shifts your ideal grind zone even with the same machine and basket. As a quick rule, lighter roasts usually need finer grind and careful puck prep to avoid thin acidity. Medium roasts are usually the easiest baseline and often sit near the center of your espresso range. Dark roasts generally extract faster, so slightly coarser settings can improve clarity and prevent harsh bitterness.</p>
  <p>Do not force every roast into the same timing target if taste says otherwise. A medium roast that tastes balanced at 24 seconds is better than a bitter 30-second shot you forced to match a rule. Use shot time as a structure, then make taste the final call. If your grinder has micro-adjust support, this is where it helps most: tiny changes to keep sweetness while preserving texture.</p>

